    <outline text="Interview and Listener Feedback">
      <outline text="Thomas Miller the creator of The Daily Grind" MediaLinks="microcore.dk—index.php &lt;http://microcore.dk/TheDailyGrind/index.php&gt;">
        <outline text="Now time for our interview today, we are talking with the creator of “The Daily Grind” widget Thomas Miller. This widget is truly amazing; it allows you to set up different timers for different events. You can name the timer, and then change the color setting for the title, it will automatically track the amount of time for each timer, you can then edit, reset, or delete the timer, as well as copying the time to the clipboard and importing that into other programs. TheDailyGrind is a Dashboard widget that offers a lightweight approach in keeping track of time spent on tasks you perform. TheDailyGrind is designed to take up as little of your time as possible managing your time to better let you focus on getting your jobs done. It was great talking with Thomas; I hope you enjoy his great widget as well as the interview.TheDailyGrind is meant to take up as little of your time managing your time. TheDailyGrind v2 has ALT-key activated shortcuts to important functions and lets you edit hours, minutes and seconds directly. Simple, neat and painless.And of course TheDailyGrind v2 retains the features of v1: add as many trackers as you need (currently limited only by vertical screen real estate), label them accordingly and start and pause them as you see fit.Copy the contents of the tracker label and the time recorded to the clipboard for use elsewhere. And naturally TheDailyGrind retains your trackers across reboots."/>
      </outline>
